{
  "text": "One of potential solutions to these problems is to use microfluidic chips due to their advantages of compactness, low-sample consumption, and low cost [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Moreover, microfluidic chip technology offers a platform to integrate sensors with functional components (e.g. microfluidic mixers) to achieve the lab-on-a-chip analysis system [CITATION_3] . Recently, it was demonstrated electrochemical glucose biosensors can be integrated into microfluidic channels to develop easy-handle, low-cost, and portable microfluidic chips [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . However, electroactive interference problems often appear in electrochemical sensors because some endogenous reducing species (e.g. ascorbic and uric acids) and drugs (e.g., acetaminophen) are electroactive [CITATION_8] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "205210989",
